The most well-known process for damping Alfvénic waves is probably phase mixing (Heyvaerts and Priest 1983), which requires a gradient in the Alfvén speed perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation. The Alfvén waves propagating along individual magnetic field lines (or magnetic surfaces) become out of phase as they propagate, generating small scales and thus increasing local gradients perpendicular to the field. The previously discussed equations for Alfvénic waves, i.e. Eqs. 1–3, are based on the ideal MHD equations. Heyvaerts and Priest (1983) demonstrated that including viscosity (ν\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
